    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-11-01T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-11-01T19:00:00-05:00" n="754"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d754">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.00/2878: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Guggenheim</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-11-01T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 1, 1930—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>128. Today’s partial congressional elections are thus far reported to have passed
                    without incident throughout Republic. Polls closed at 3 p.m.; the efforts of
                    Nationalists and the Menocal group of Conservatives to persuade abstention from
                    voting had limited response. Military and police reserves for maintenance of
                    order not used, although undoubtedly public knowledge of precautionary measures
                    had salutary effect.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Guggenheim</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
